  "text": "ously [CITATION_1] , all truncation mutants except for the deletion of the N-terminal 8 ␣-synuclein residues were unable to promote SNARE-complex assembly (Figs. 5, 6 ). Thus, both phospholipid binding mediated by the ␣-helices of ␣-synuclein and synaptobrevin-2 binding mediated by the C-terminal ␣-synuclein sequence (Figs. 2, 4) are required for the ability of ␣-synuclein to promote SNAREcomplex assembly. In contrast to the truncation mutants, only one point mutant of ␣-synuclein, the A30P mutation, impaired the ability of ␣-synuclein to promote SNARE-complex assembly. The others, including the PD mutants E46K and A53T, did not. Thus, partial impairment of phospholipid binding, as observed with most of these point mutants (Fig. 2) , does not by itself block the function of ␣-synuclein to promote SNAREcomplex assembly. The A30P mutation is unique among the ␣-synuclein point mutants in that it did impair SNAREcomplex assembly, possibly due to impaired synaptic targeting (Fig. 3) .",
